Statistical analysis was performed using linear mixed-effects models using the lme4 package65. By incorporating fixed and random effects, these models are appropriate for data from the same subject over time and enable more powerful analysis of longitudinal studies. The model formula is given below:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$y_{ij} = \mathop {\sum}\limits_{p = 1}^P \alpha _pX_{pij} + \mathop {\sum}\limits_{r = 0}^R \beta _{ri}Z_{rij} + \varepsilon _{ij}$$\end{document}yij= ∑p=1PαpXpij+ ∑r=0RβriZrij+εijIn (1), for a particular mouse i measured at a particular time point j, yij is the response variable we want to model, P is the total number of fixed effects, the matrix X represents our fixed effects with Xpij and αp being the value of the pth fixed effect and its coefficient, R is the total number of random effects, the matrix Z represents our random effects with Zrij and βri representing the value of the rth random effect for the ith mouse and its coefficient, and εij represent the residuals assumed to be independent and normally distributed. Wherever possible, we qualitatively checked if the residuals of the linear mixed-effects models were normally distributed.

To perform significance testing for a set of q effects (i.e. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
